%META:TOPICINFO{author="EelcoVisser" date="1030096230" format="1.0" version="1.1"}%
d3 1
d5 1
a5 1
<h3><a href="http://www.stratego-language.org">Stratego - Program Transformation</a></h3>
d7 1
a7 3
Stratego is a language for the specification of program
		transformation systems based on the paradigm of rewriting
		strategies. 
d9 1
a9 9
		The basic transformation steps are specified by means of
		conditional rewrite rules. The individual rewrite rules are
		combined into a transformation system by means of a strategy, a
		program in a dedicated language of strategy combinators. This
		language supports controlled application of rewrite rules and
		concise description of traversals over abstract syntax trees.
		
		This entails a separation of concerns between specification of
		the transformation rules and the control of their application.
d11 1
a11 3
		<p></p>
The Stratego compiler (<em>sc</em>) translates a specification
		to a C program.
d13 1
a13 7
<h3><a href="http://www.program-transformation.org/Tools/SDF2">SDF2 - Syntax Definition</a></h3> SDF2 is a formalism for syntax definition.
		
		One of its key innovative features is the full integration of
		lexical and context-free syntax. This entails that all aspects
		of the syntax of a language can be described in one
		formalism. At the implementation level this entails that no
		separate scanner is needed.
d15 1
a15 69
		In addition, the formalism provides a number of features that
		make syntax definitions concise: modules, priorities, follow
		restrictions, reject productions, a wide range of regular
		expressions, aliases and character ranges.

		<p />

The implementation of SDF2 consists of a parser generator (pgen)
		that generates parse tables and an interpreter for these tables
		(sglr) that parses files.  The implementation is not yet
		available for distribution.

<h3><a href="http://www.program-transformation.org/Tools/GrammarTools">GT - Grammar Tools</a></h3> GT is a collection of tools for grammar engineering.

<h3><a href="http://www.program-transformation.org/Tools/GrammarBase">GB - Grammar Base</a></h3>

GB is a collection of syntax definitions for common languages.

<h3><a href="http://www.program-transformation.org/Tools/XT">XT - Transformation Tools</a></h3>

Distribution of a number of tools for the construction of
		program transformation systems.

	  <p />

The package includes
		<ul>
<li> ATerm library
	<li> Stratego : specification of program transformation systems
	<li> GPP : generic pretty-printing package
	<li> SGLR : scannerless generalized LR parser </li>
<li> PGEN : parser generator for SDF2 </li>
<li> GB : grammar base
	<li> GT : grammar tools
		</ul>

<h3><a href="http://www.stratego-language.org/Hpc/TigerInStratego">Tiger in Stratego</a></h3>

Implementation of a compiler for Andrew Appe's Tiger language as a case study in compilation by
	  transformation. Used in a course on <a href="http://www.stratego-language.org/Hpc">High-Performance Compilers</a>.

<h3><a href="http://www.cs.uu.nl/~visser/ftp/dir.shar">Dir Package - Modularity for LaTeX</a></h3>

The <em>dir</em> package is a small (La)TeX package that
		supports true modularity for LaTeX. It allows one to
		transparantly input a file in another directory without having
		to adapt all the inputs in the included file.

		<p />

<em>Usage</em> Put <code>\usepackage{dir}</code> in the preamble
		of your document. To input a (collection of) files in another
		directory: <code>{\cd{/the/other/directory}
		\input{file.ltx}}</code>. Due to the <code>\cd</code> command,
		all <code>\input<code>s will be relative to
		<code>/the/other/directory</code>.

		<em>Note</em> The above is the only documentation about the
		package.

<h3><a href="http://www.cs.uu.nl/~visser/ftp/thesis.cls">Thesis - LaTeX document class</a></h3>

LaTeX document class that I wrote for my <a href="../thesis/index.html">PhD thesis</a>. 

<h3><a href="http://www.cs.uu.nl/~visser/ftp/stop-report.cls">STOP-report - LaTeX document class</a></h3>

LaTeX document class supporting the production of reports and
		proposals in the style of <em>Sequential Topic-Oriented
		Publications</em>. 
d17 1
